BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:foPcpozQ5GZVGjSWYSpzz
SUMMARY:Marlon James
DTSTAMP:20260413T050902Z
DTSTART:20260506T193000Z
DESCRIPTION:Marlon James won the 2015 Man Booker Prize for Fiction for A Br
	ief History of Seven Killings\\\, making him the first Jamaican author to 
	take home the U.K.’s most prestigious literary award. In the work\\\, Jame
	s combines masterful storytelling with brilliant skill at characterization
	 and an eye for detail to forge a bold novel of dazzling ambition and scop
	e. He explores Jamaican history through the perspectives of multiple narra
	tors and genres: the political thriller\\\, the oral biography\\\, and the
	 classic whodunit confront the untold history of Jamaica in the 1970’s\\\,
	 with excursions to the assassination attempt on reggae musician Bob Marle
	y\\\, as well as the country’s own clandestine battles during the cold war
	. \\nJames cites influences as diverse as Greek tragedy\\\, William Faulkn
	er\\\, the LA crime novelist James Ellroy\\\, Shakespeare\\\, Batman\\\, a
	nd the X-Men. Writing for The New York Times\\\, Michiko Kakutani said of 
	A Brief History of Seven Killings\\\, “It’s epic in every sense of that wo
	rd: sweeping\\\, mythic\\\, over-the-top\\\, colossal and dizzyingly compl
	ex. It’s also raw\\\, dense\\\, violent\\\, scalding\\\, darkly comic\\\, 
	exhilarating\\\, and exhausting—a testament to Mr. James’s vaulting ambiti
	on and prodigious talent.” In addition to the Man Booker Prize\\\, A Brief
	 History of Seven Killings won the American Book Award\\\, the Anisfield-W
	olf Book Prize\\\, the OCM Bocas Prize for Caribbean Literature\\\, the Mi
	nnesota Book Award\\\, and was a finalist for the National Book Critics Ci
	rcle Award. \\nMarlon James’ first novel\\\, John Crow’s Devil\\\, tells t
	he story of a biblical struggle in a remote Jamaican village in the 1950s.
	 Though rejected 78 times before being accepted for publication\\\, John C
	row’s Devil went on to become a finalist for the Los Angeles Times Book Pr
	ize and the Commonwealth Writers Prize\\\, as well as a New York Times Edi
	tor’s Choice. His second novel\\\, The Book of Night Women\\\, is about a 
	slave woman’s revolt on a Jamaican plantation in the early 19th century. \
	\nThe work won the 2010 Dayton Literary Peace Prize\\\, Minnesota Book Awa
	rd\\\, and was a finalist for the 2010 National Book Critics Circle Award 
	in fiction\\\, as well as an NAACP Image Award. His best-selling book\\\, 
	Black Leopard\\\, Red Wolf\\\, is the first in the Dark Star Trilogy\\\, a
	 fantasy series set in African legend. Black Leopard\\\, Red Wolf received
	 the Ray Bradbury Prize for Science Fiction\\\, Fantasy and Speculative Fi
	ction from the Los Angeles Times Book Prizes\\\, the 2020 Locus Award for 
	Horror\\\, was a finalist for the 2019 National Book Award in the Fiction 
	category\\\, was named one of the Washington Post‘s 10 Best Books of 2019\
	\\, and was included in the Kirkus list for The Best Books of the 21st Cen
	tury (So Far). The second book in the trilogy\\\, Moon Witch\\\, Spider Ki
	ng\\\, was an instant New York Times Bestseller. The third book will be ti
	tled White Wing\\\, Dark Star (Random House). \\nJames’ short fiction and 
	nonfiction have been anthologized in Bronx Noir\\\, The Book of Men: Eight
	y Writers on How to Be a Man and elsewhere\\\, and have appeared in Esquir
	e\\\, Granta\\\, Harper’s\\\, The Caribbean Review of Books\\\, and other 
	publications. His widely read essay\\\, “From Jamaica to Minnesota to Myse
	lf\\\,” appeared in the New York Times Magazine. In early 2016\\\, his vir
	al video Are you racist? ‘No’ isn’t a good enough answer received millions
	 of hits. James hosts a popular podcast about literature with Jake Morriss
	ey called Marlon and Jake Read Dead People. He provided commentary for The
	 Adventures of Huckleberry Finn from ReBind. Marlon James wrote and is exe
	cutive producer for Get Millie Black a 6-part crime drama set in Jamaica f
	or movie channel HBO and the UK’s Channel 4.\n\nhttps://townhallseattle.or
	g/event/marlon-james/\n\nFrom Town Hall Seattle
URL:https://townhallseattle.org/event/marlon-james/
LOCATION:The Great Hall\\\, 1119 Eighth Avenue (enter on Eighth Avenue)\\\,
	 Seattle\\\, 98101\\\, United States
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:town-hall-seattle
CATEGORIES:Town Hall Seattle
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:qEpBHl5gQWPIwyYG6jh7D
SUMMARY:Celebrating Bike Everywhere Month 2026
DTSTAMP:20260413T050902Z
DTSTART:20260506T193000Z
DESCRIPTION:Do you bike in Seattle — or want to? Join Cascade Bike Club for
	 Town Hall Seattle’s 2nd annual Bike Month Bash. \\nSeattle’s bike network
	 and transit connections are expanding as the city prepares for the FIFA W
	orld Cup and a flood of visitors this summer. But gaps remain\\\, and more
	 work is needed to make people of all abilities feel safe biking in our ci
	ty. There are also many opportunities to support better biking in Seattle\
	\\, such as the Pedaling Relief Project that rescues and delivers food on 
	behalf of multiple food banks. Bring your enthusiasm and questions for our
	 panel of speakers representing Cascade Bicycle Club\\\, the Seattle Stree
	ts Alliance\\\, and the Seattle Bike Blog. Learn about opportunities to pu
	sh progress and participate in a Summer of Seattle Cycling! \\nBike parkin
	g will be provided. \\n\\nPresented by Town Hall Seattle and Cascade Bicyc
	le Club. \\n \\nEvents are offered for informational\\\, entertainment\\\,
	 and educational purposes only. Read Town Hall’s Program Content Policy.\n
	\nhttps://townhallseattle.org/event/celebrating-bike-everywhere-month-2026
	/\n\nFrom Town Hall Seattle
URL:https://townhallseattle.org/event/celebrating-bike-everywhere-month-202
	6/
LOCATION:The Wyncote NW Forum\\\, 1119 8th Ave (Entrance off Seneca St.)\\\
	, Seattle\\\, 98101\\\, United States
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:town-hall-seattle
CATEGORIES:Town Hall Seattle
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:BNGhjTvuB4B3OBxjjGShu
SUMMARY:Screen Printing Open Session
DTSTAMP:20260413T050902Z
DTSTART:20260506T230000Z
DESCRIPTION:You MUST take the SP 101: Intro to Vera's Screen Print Studio c
	lass before you can sign up for an Open Session\n\nVera’s screen print stu
	dio offers four-hour Open Sessions where individuals who have completed th
	e introductory class may use our screen print lab to work on their own pro
	jects. Our Open Sessions are looked over by a volunteer moderator\, who ca
	n provide you with advice and guidance for anything taught in our Screen P
	rinting 101 class. We offer three different kinds of tickets at Open Sessi
	ons: Vacuum Table for paper and other flat media\, T-shirt Press for shirt
	s\, tote bags and other fabrics\, and Screen prep for just screen preparat
	ion. Each ticket is limited to two. If the ticket you are looking for is s
	old out\, please add yourself to the waitlist so you can be notified when 
	a ticket becomes available.\n\nFor Open Sessions\, Vera provides:\n\n- Ren
	table screens\n- Emulsion and emulsion remover\n- Squegees\n- Basic tools 
	like spatulas\, rulers\, tape\, etc.\n\nParticipants must provide their ow
	n:\n\n- Substrate (paper\, t-shirts\, etc)\n- Water based ink\n\nVera does
	 not allow the use of non-water based inks at our studio\, as our studio i
	s not set up to safely process non-water based ink.\n\nIf you have any que
	stions\, please email matt@theveraproject.org.\n\nFAQ\n\n1\\. Can Vera pri
	nt a transparent stencil for me?\n\nYes — You must send us your stencil at
	 least 24 hours before the start of your session. Your file must be a .PDF
	\, no larger than 12" x 18"\, and ready to print. Vera cannot make any edi
	ts to your file. Stencils are $5 each and can be paid via Debit/Credit whe
	n you arrive.\n\nIf you are not interested in getting a stencil printed at
	 Vera\, you can print your own on transparency at a FedEx or similar print
	 service location.\n\n2\\. What if I need direct assistance on my projects
	?\n\nOur moderators are trained to assist with any topics covered in the S
	P 101 class offered at Vera. While some may be able to give you basic advi
	ce on your project\, they are not expected to ask as a direct instructor. 
	If you have a project where you would like one-on-one guidance\, please re
	ach out to matt@theveraproject.org to request private tutoring.\n\n3\\. I 
	really want to use your studio during an Open Session\, but there are no s
	lots available?\n\nOur studio is in high demand\, so we apologize if our O
	pen Session is sold out — We have limited space in the studio and several 
	events every day at Vera\, so it can be difficult for us to find more time
	 for Open Sessions. If you're interested in booking the studio outside of 
	Open Sessions\, please email matt@theveraproject.org to discuss private re
	ntal rates and availability.\n\nhttps://link.dice.fm/t19107936d5d\n\nFrom 
	The Vera Project
URL:https://link.dice.fm/t19107936d5d
LOCATION:305 Harrison Street\, Seattle\, Washington 98109\, United States
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:vera-project
CATEGORIES:The Vera Project
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT4H
END:VEVENT
